## Part 7 — HTTPS Setup

### Option A — Free domain + Let's Encrypt (recommended if you own/can get a domain)
```bash
sudo apt install -y certbot python3-certbot-nginx
sudo certbot --nginx -d yourdomain.com
```
Certbot auto-edits your Nginx config and sets up auto-renewal.

### Option B — No domain: self-signed cert (for demo purposes only)
```bash
sudo mkdir -p /etc/nginx/ssl
sudo openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 \
  -keyout /etc/nginx/ssl/selfsigned.key \
  -out /etc/nginx/ssl/selfsigned.crt \
  -subj "/CN=<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>"
```
Then add a `listen 443 ssl;` server block in Nginx referencing these files. Browsers will show a warning (expected — no CA signed it), but it demonstrates HTTPS configuration for the assignment.

Also update your Security Group: port 443 inbound should already be open from Part 2.

