## Part 10 — Load Testing with k6

Script is at `load-test/script.js`.

### 10.1 Install k6 (run this from your local machine, not EC2, to simulate real external users)
```bash
# macOS
brew install k6
# Ubuntu/Debian
sudo gpg -k
sudo gpg --no-default-keyring --keyring /usr/share/keyrings/k6-archive-keyring.gpg --keyserver hkp://keyserver.ubuntu.com:80 --recv-keys C5AD17C747E3415A3642D57D77C6C491D6AC1D69
echo "deb [signed-by=/usr/share/keyrings/k6-archive-keyring.gpg] https://dl.k6.io/deb stable main" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/k6.list
sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get install k6
```

### 10.2 Run the test
```bash
k6 run --env BASE_URL=http://<EC2_PUBLIC_IP> load-test/script.js
```

### 10.3 Metrics k6 gives you automatically (record these in your report)
- `http_req_duration` — latency (avg, p90, p95, p99)
- `http_reqs` — throughput (requests/sec)
- `http_req_failed` — error rate
- Combine with the CloudWatch dashboard (CPU/memory) captured **during the same test window** to correlate load with resource usage.

### 10.4 Export results as HTML/JSON for your report
```bash
k6 run --out json=results.json --env BASE_URL=http://<EC2_PUBLIC_IP> load-test/script.js
```
Use a tool like [k6 HTML reporter](https://github.com/benc-uk/k6-reporter) or simply paste key metrics + a screenshot of terminal output into your report.

